{
  "id": "019d32ce-3488-7643-9941-f543135db6e3",
  "content": "# Decision: Native Structural Intelligence Roadmap — P1-P6 Then Expand\n\n## Context\n\nEvaluated GitNexus (19k stars, Feb 2026) as a complement or integration target for corvia's repo onboarding cold-start problem. GitNexus builds code knowledge graphs with Leiden clustering, execution flow tracing, blast radius analysis, and 14-language support. However, its output is locked in LadybugDB with no portable export format, making adapter integration fragile.\n\n## Decision\n\nBuild native structural intelligence in corvia's adapter-git in two phases:\n\n### Phase 1: P1-P6 (Core Structural Intelligence)\n\n| Priority | What | Effort | Impact |\n|----------|------|--------|--------|\n| P1 | JS/TS: add `extends`/`implements` + `calls` extraction in treesitter.rs | Medium | High |\n| P2 | Python: add class inheritance + `calls` extraction in treesitter.rs | Medium | High |\n| P3 | JS/TS target resolution: `index.ts`, path aliases, package.json exports | Low-Medium | High |\n| P4 | Edge weight scoring by relation type in retriever.rs GraphExpandRetriever | Low | Medium |\n| P5 | HashMap optimization in `wire_pipeline_relations()` for large repos | Low | Low-Medium |\n| P6 | LLM-assisted architectural summaries — synthesize \"how does X work?\" entries post-ingest | High | High |\n\nThis leverages existing infrastructure: tree-sitter parsing, ChunkRelation pipeline, wire_pipeline_relations(), GraphStore, and GraphExpandRetriever are all fully wired end-to-end (validated by M4.2 fix, 552 relations stored on corvia repo).\n\n### Phase 2: Expand Toward GitNexus Parity (Future)\n\nAfter P1-P6 ships, incrementally add:\n- Leiden community clustering (functional subsystem detection with cohesion scores)\n- Execution flow tracing (entry point to terminal call chain mapping)\n- Blast radius / impact analysis (confidence-scored, depth-grouped)\n- Change detection (git diff to affected processes mapping)\n- Additional language support (Java, Go, C/C++, Kotlin — currently 4, GitNexus has 14)\n- Framework-aware entry point detection (Express routes, React components, Django views)\n- Confidence scoring on relations\n\n## Rationale\n\n- P1-P6 closes the cold-start gap: `corvia workspace ingest` produces navigable code structure on day one\n- Corvia's moat is organizational memory, knowledge lifecycle, multi-agent coordination, and temporal reasoning — GitNexus doesn't touch these\n- Deep code analysis (clustering, blast radius, flows) is nice-to-have but not core to corvia's value proposition\n- The two tools can coexist: corvia for org memory + structural basics, GitNexus alongside for deep code analysis if teams want it\n- No GitNexus integration/adapter: their output is locked in LadybugDB with no export format, undocumented schema, and MCP responses designed for LLM consumption not data interchange\n\n## Key Files\n\n- `adapters/corvia-adapter-git/rust/src/treesitter.rs` — relation extraction per language\n- `adapters/corvia-adapter-git/rust/src/ast_chunker.rs` — ChunkRelation mapping\n- `crates/corvia-kernel/src/ingest.rs` — `wire_pipeline_relations()` wiring\n- `crates/corvia-kernel/src/retriever.rs` — GraphExpandRetriever scoring\n- `crates/corvia-kernel/src/graph_store.rs` — edge storage (LiteStore)\n\n## Prior Art\n\n- M4.2 RFC (2026-03-04): Fixed relation wiring, proved pipeline works end-to-end\n- M3.4 RFC: Graph edge improvements design\n- GitNexus evaluation: no portable export, LadybugDB-locked, schema undocumented",
  "source_version": "mcp",
